and":"Yorkshire, England","Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Insula","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from any of the places called Insua, meaning ‘island, peninsula (of a river or of the sea), land by a river’, from Latin <i>insula</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Insula was born about 1155, his father, Robert de Insula, was 30 and his mother, Galiena Blount, was 27. He married Beatrice de Cormeilles in 1189, in Harewood, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after 1213, in England."},"et":{"Abt 1155–after 1213":"umbes 1155–pärast 1213","1155–1213":"1155–1213","1160–1250":"1160–1250","1150–1220":"1150–1220","1186–1223":"1186–1223","1190–1213":"1190–1213","1126–1186":"1126–1186","1130–1175":"1130–1175","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1130":"1130","1250":"1250","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1126":"1126","1213":"1213","1223":"1223","Abt 1155":"umbes 1155","1189":"1189","1155":"1155","after 1213":"pärast 1213","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1155–after 1213":"noin 1155–1213 jälkeen","1155–1213":"1155–1213","1160–1250":"1160–1250","1150–1220":"1150–1220","1186–1223":"1186–1223","1190–1213":"1190–1213","1126–1186":"1126–1186","1130–1175":"1130–1175","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1130":"1130","1250":"1250","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1126":"1126","1213":"1213","1223":"1223","Abt 1155":"noin 1155","1189":"1189","1155":"1155","after 1213":"1213 jälkeen","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Rampton, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1155–after 1213":"environ 1155–après 1213","1155–1213":"1155–1213","1160–1250":"1160–1250","1150–1220":"1150–1220","1186–1223":"1186–1223","1190–1213":"1190–1213","1126–1186":"1126–1186